               <p>JOHN OLIVER. I am an <rs id="t18270913-369-viclabel2050" type="occupation">upholsterer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-369-victim2640 t18270913-369-viclabel2050"></join>, and live in <placeName id="t18270913-369-crimeloc2051">Houndsditch</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-369-crimeloc2051" type="placeName" value="Houndsditch"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18270913-369-crimeloc2051" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18270913-369-off2048 t18270913-369-crimeloc2051"></join>. I lost some rush-matting on the 14th of September, between two and three o'clock, while I was at dinner- I had seen it safe an hour or two before.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-369-person2641">
                  MARY 
                  HODDER
               <interp inst="t18270913-369-person2641" type="surname" value="HODDER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-369-person2641" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18270913-369-person2641" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Leathersellers' Alms-houses. I was standing to rest my basket, opposite Mr. Oliver's door; I saw the prisoner go into the shop empty-handed, and come out with a roll of matting on his shoulder - I went in and told Shaw, who was rubbing chairs at the bottom of the shop. I am certain of his person; he was alone.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18270913-369-person2642">
